#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:31
msgid ""
"Current Linux systems have graphical utilities dedicated to the work of an "
"administrator. However, it is important to be able to use the interface in "
"command line mode for several reasons:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:37
msgid ""
"The majority of system commands are common to all Linux distributions, which "
"is not the case for graphical tools."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:37
msgid ""
"It can happen that the system does not start correctly but that a backup "
"command interpreter remains accessible."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:37
msgid "Remote administration is done on the command line with an SSH terminal."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:37
msgid ""
"In order to preserve server resources, the graphical interface is either not "
"installed or launched on demand."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:37
msgid "Administration is done by scripts."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:39
msgid ""
"Learning these commands allows the administrator to connect to a Linux "
"terminal, to manage its resources and files, to identify the station, the "
"terminal, and the connected users, etc."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:40
#, no-wrap
msgid "The users"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:43
msgid ""
"The user of a Linux system will be defined in the `/etc/passwd` file, by:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:49
msgid "A **login name**, more commonly called \"login\", containing no spaces."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:49
msgid "A numeric identifier: **UID** (User Identifier)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:49
msgid "A group identifier: **GID** (Group Identifier)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:49
msgid ""
"A **command interpreter**, e.g., a shell, which can be different from one "
"user to another."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:49
msgid "A **connection directory**, e.g., the __home directory__."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:51
msgid "In other files the user will be defined by:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:54
msgid "A **password**, which is encrypted before being stored (`/etc/shadow`)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:54
msgid ""
"A **command prompt**, or __prompt__ login, which is symbolized by a `#` for "
"administrators and a `$` for other users (`/etc/profile`)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:56
msgid ""
"Depending on the security policy implemented on the system, the password "
"will require a certain number of characters and meet certain complexity "
"requirements."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:58
msgid ""
"Among the existing command interpreters, the **Bourne-Again Shell** (`/bin/"
"bash`) is the one most frequently used. It is assigned by default to new "
"users. For various reasons, advanced Linux users can choose alternative "
"shells such as the Korn Shell (`ksh`), the C Shell (`csh`), etc."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:60
msgid ""
"The user's login directory is by convention stored in the `/home` directory "
"of the workstation. It will contain the user's personal data and the "
"configuration files of his applications. By default, at login, the login "
"directory is selected as the current directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:62
#, no-wrap
msgid "A workstation-type installation (with graphical interface) starts this interface on terminal 1. Linux being multi-user, it is possible to connect several users several times, on different **physical terminals** (TTY) or **virtual terminals** (PTS). Virtual terminals are available within a graphical environment. A user switches from one physical terminal to another using <kbd>Alt</kbd> + <kbd>Fx</kbd> from the command line or using <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>Alt</kbd> + <kbd>Fx</kbd>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:63
#, no-wrap
msgid "The shell"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:66
msgid ""
"Once the user is connected to a console, the shell displays the **command "
"prompt**. It then behaves like an infinite loop, repeating the same pattern "
"with each statement entered:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:74
msgid "Displays the command prompt."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:74
msgid "Reads the command."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:74
msgid "Analyzes the syntax."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:74
msgid "Substitutes special characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:74
msgid "Executes the command."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:74
msgid "Etc."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:76
#, no-wrap
msgid "The key sequence <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>C</kbd> is used to interrupt a running command.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:78
msgid "The use of a command generally follows this sequence:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:79
#, no-wrap
msgid "command [option(s)] [arguments(s)]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:84
msgid "The name of the command is often **lower case**."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:86
msgid "A space separates each item."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:89
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**Short options** begin with a dash (`-l`), while **long options** begin with two dashes (`--list`).\n"
"A double dash (`--`) indicates the end of the option list.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:91
msgid "It is possible to group some short options together:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:92
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ ls -l -i -a\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:97
msgid "is equivalent to:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:98
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ ls -lia\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:103
msgid "There can be several arguments after an option:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:104
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ ls -lia /etc /home /var\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:109
msgid ""
"In the literature, the term \"option\" is equivalent to the term \"parameter,"
"\" which is more commonly used in programming. The optional side of an "
"option or argument is symbolized by enclosing it in square brackets `[` and "
"`]`. When more than one option is possible, a vertical bar called a \"pipe\" "
"separates them `[a|e|i]`."
