msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:285
msgid ""
"This command is most commonly used in administration scripts to inform the "
"user during execution."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:287
msgid ""
"The `-n` option indicates no newline output string (by default, newline "
"output string)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:288
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"shell > echo -n \"123\";echo \"456\"\n"
"123456\n"
"\n"
"shell > echo \"123\";echo \"456\"\n"
"123\n"
"456\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:298
msgid ""
"For various reasons, the script developer may need to use special sequences "
"(starting with a `\\` character). In this case, the `-e` option will be "
"stipulated, allowing interpretation of the sequences."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:300
msgid "Among the frequently used sequences, we can mention:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:308
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Sequence | Result                |\n"
"| -------- | --------------------- |\n"
"| `\\a`     | Sends a sonar beep      |\n"
"| `\\b`     | Back                  |\n"
"| `\\n`     | Adds a line break     |\n"
"| `\\t`     | Adds a horizontal tab |\n"
"| `\\v`     | Adds a vertical tab     |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:309
#, no-wrap
msgid "`date` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:312
msgid ""
"The `date` command displays the date and time. The command has the following "
"syntax:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:313
#, no-wrap
msgid "date [-d yyyyMMdd] [format]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:319
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ date\n"
"Mon May 24 16:46:53 CEST 2021\n"
"$ date -d 20210517 +%j\n"
"137\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:327
msgid ""
"In this last example, the `-d` option displays a given date. The `+%j` "
"option formats this date to show only the day of the year."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:329
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1266
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1325
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1480
msgid "!!! Warning"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:331
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The format of a date can change depending on the value of the language defined in the environment variable `$LANG`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:333
msgid "The date display can follow the following formats:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:353
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option  | Format                                                    |\n"
"| --------| --------------------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `+%A`   | Locale's full weekday name (e.g., Sunday)                 |\n"
"| `+%B`   | Locale's full month name (e.g., January)                  |\n"
"| `+%c`   | Locale's date and time (e.g., Thu Mar  3 23:05:25 2005)   |\n"
"| `+%d`   | Day of month (e.g., 01)                                   |\n"
"| `+%F`   | Date in `YYYY-MM-DD` format                               |\n"
"| `+%G`   | Year                                                      |\n"
"| `+%H`   | Hour (00..23)                                             |\n"
"| `+%j`   | Day of the year (001..366)                                |\n"
"| `+%m`   | Month number (01..12)                                     |\n"
"| `+%M`   | Minute  (00..59)                                          |\n"
"| `+%R`   | Time in `hh:mm` format                                    |\n"
"| `+%s`   | Seconds since January 1, 1970                             |\n"
"| `+%S`   | Second (00..60)                                           |\n"
"| `+%T`   | Time in `hh:mm:ss` format                                 |\n"
"| `+%u`   | Day of the week (`1` for Monday)                          |\n"
"| `+%V`   | Week number (`+%V`)                                       |\n"
"| `+%x`   | Date in format `DD/MM/YYYY`                               |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:355
msgid ""
"The `date` command also allows you to change the system date and time. In "
"this case, the `-s` option will be used."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:356
#, no-wrap
msgid "[root]# date -s \"2021-05-24 10:19\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:361
msgid "The format to be used following the `-s` option is this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:362
#, no-wrap
msgid "date -s \"yyyy-MM-dd hh:mm[:ss]\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:366
#, no-wrap
msgid "`id`, `who` and `whoami` commands"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:369
msgid ""
"The `id` command is used to display information about users and groups. By "
"default, no user parameter is added, and the information of the currently "
"logged in user and group is displayedã"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:370
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ id rockstar\n"
"uid=1000(rockstar) gid=1000(rockstar) groups=1000(rockstar),10(wheel)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:376
msgid ""
"The `-g`, `-G`, `-n` and `-u` options display the main group GID, subgroup "
"GIDs, names instead of numeric identifiers, and the user's UID respectively."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:378
msgid "The `whoami` command displays the login of the current user."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:380
msgid "The `who` command alone displays the names of logged in users:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:381
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ who\n"
"rockstar tty1   2021-05-24 10:30\n"
"root     pts/0  2021-05-24 10:31\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:388
msgid ""
"Since Linux is multi-user, it is possible that multiple sessions are open on "
"the same station, either physically or over the network. It is interesting "
"to know which users are logged in, if only to communicate with them by "
"sending messages."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:391
msgid "tty: represents a terminal."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:391
msgid ""
"pts/: represents a virtual console in a graphical environment with the "
"number after representing the instance of the virtual console (0, 1, 2...)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:393
msgid "The `-r` option also displays the runlevel (see chapter \"startup\")."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:394
#, no-wrap
msgid "File Tree"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:397
msgid ""
"In Linux, the file tree is an inverted tree, called a **single hierarchical "
"tree**, whose root is the directory `/`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:399
msgid "The **current directory** is the directory where the user is located."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:401
msgid ""
"The **connection directory** is the working directory associated with the "
"user. The login directories are, by default, stored in the `/home` directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:403
msgid "When the user logs in, the current directory is the login directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:405
msgid ""
"An **absolute path** references a file from the root by traversing the "
"entire tree to the file level:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:407
msgid "`/home/groupA/alice/file`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:409
msgid ""
"The **relative path** references that same file by traversing the entire "
"tree from the current directory:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:411
msgid "`../alice/file`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:413
msgid ""
"In the above example, the \"`..`\" refers to the parent directory of the "
"current directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:415
msgid ""
"A directory, even if it is empty, will necessarily contain at least **two "
"references**:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:418
msgid "`.`: reference to itself."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:418
msgid "`..`: reference to the parent directory of the current directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:420
msgid ""
"A relative path can thus start with `./` or `../`. When the relative path "
"refers to a subdirectory or file in the current directory, then the `./` is "
"often omitted. Mentioning the first `./` in the tree will only really be "
"required to run an executable file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:422
msgid ""
"Errors in paths can cause many problems: creating folders or files in the "
"wrong places, unintentional deletions, etc. It is therefore strongly "
"recommended to use auto-completion when entering paths."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:424
msgid "![our example tree](images/commands-pathabsolute.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:426
msgid ""
"In the above example, we are looking to give the location of the file "
"`myfile` from the directory of bob."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:429
msgid ""
"By an **absolute path**, the current directory does not matter. We start at "
"the root, and work our way down to the directories `home`, `groupA`, `alice` "
"and finally the file `myfile`: `/home/groupA/alice/myfile`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:429
msgid ""
"By a **relative path**, our starting point being the current directory "
"`bob`, we go up one level through `..` (i.e., into the `groupA` directory), "
"then down into the alice directory, and finally the `myfile` file: `../alice/"
"myfile`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:430
#, no-wrap
msgid "`pwd` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:433
msgid ""
"The `pwd` (Print Working Directory) command displays the absolute path of "
"the current directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:434
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ pwd\n"
"/home/rockstar\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:440
msgid ""
"To use a relative path to reference a file or directory, or use the `cd` "
"command to move to another directory, you must know its location in the file "
"tree."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:442
msgid ""
"Depending on the type of shell and the different parameters of its "
"configuration file, the terminal prompt (also known as the command prompt) "
"will display the absolute or relative path of the current directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:443
#, no-wrap
msgid "`cd` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:446
msgid ""
"The `cd` (Change Directory) command allows you to change the current "
"directory -- in other words, to move through the tree."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:447
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ cd /tmp\n"
"$ pwd\n"
"/tmp\n"
"$ cd ../\n"
"$ pwd\n"
"/\n"
"$ cd\n"
"$ pwd\n"
"/home/rockstar\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:460
msgid ""
"As you can see in the last example above, the command `cd` with no arguments "
"moves the current directory to the `home directory`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:461
#, no-wrap
msgid "`ls` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:464
msgid "The `ls` command displays the contents of a directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:465
#, no-wrap
msgid "ls [-a] [-i] [-l] [directory1] [directory2] [â¦]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:471
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ ls /home\n"
".    ..    rockstar\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:477
msgid "The main options of the `ls` command are:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:483
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                                                       | Information                                                                                                                          |\n"
"| ------------------------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |\n"
"| `-a`                                                         | Displays all files, even hidden ones. Hidden files in Linux are those beginning with `.`.                                            |\n"
"| `-i`                                                         | Displays inode numbers.                                                                                                              |\n"
"| `-l`                                                         | Use a long listing format, that is, each line displays long format information for a file or directory.                                 |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:485
msgid "The `ls` command, however, has a lot of options (see `man`):"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:496
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                                                       | Information                                                                                                                          |\n"
"| ------                                                       | ------------                                                                                                                         |\n"
"| `-d`                                                         | Displays information about a directory instead of listing its contents.                                                              |\n"
"| `-g`                                                         | Like -l option, but do not list owner.                                                                                               |\n"
"| `-h`                                                         | Displays file sizes in the most appropriate format (byte, kilobyte, megabyte, gigabyte, ...). `h` stands for Human Readable. Needs to be used with -l option.         |\n"
"| `-s`                                                         | Displays the allocated size of each file, in blocks. In the GNU/Linux operating system, \"block\" is the smallest unit of storage in the file system, one block equals 4096Byte. |\n"
"| `-A`                                                         | Displays all files in the directory except `.` and `..`                                                                              |\n"
"| `-R`                                                         | Displays the contents of subdirectories recursively.                                                                                 |\n"
"| `-F`                                                         | Displays the type of files. Prints a `/` for a directory, `*` for executables, `@` for a symbolic link, and nothing for a text file. |\n"
"| `-X`                                                         | Sorts files according to their extensions.                                                                                           |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:498
msgid "Description of columns generated by running the `ls -lia` command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:499
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ ls -lia /home\n"
"78489 drwx------ 4 rockstar rockstar 4096 25 oct. 08:10 rockstar\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:514
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Value           | Information                                                                                                   |\n"
"| --------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `78489`         | Inode Number.                                                                                                 |\n"
"| `drwx------`    | File type (`d`) and rights (`rwx------`).                                                                     |\n"
"| `4`             | Number of subdirectories (`.` and `..` included). For a file, it represents the number of hard links, and 1 represents itself. |\n"
"| `rockstar`      | User ownership.                                                                                               |\n"
"| `rockstar`      | Group ownership.                                                                                              |\n"
"| `4096`          | For files, it shows the size of the file. For directories, it shows the fixed value of 4096 bytes occupied by the file naming. To calculate the total size of a directory, use `du -sh rockstar/` |\n"
"| `25 oct. 08:10` | Last modified date.                                                                                           |\n"
"| `rockstar`      | The name of the file (or directory).                                                                          |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:516
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:693
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1216
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1262
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1297
msgid "!!! Note"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:518
#, no-wrap
msgid "    **Aliases** are frequently positioned in common distributions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:520
#, no-wrap
msgid "    This is the case of the alias `ll`:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:524
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    ```\n"
"    alias ll='ls -l --color=auto'\n"
"    ```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:526
msgid ""
"The `ls` command has many options. Here are some advanced examples of uses:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:528
msgid "List the files in `/etc` in order of last modification:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:529
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ ls -ltr /etc\n"
"total 1332\n"
"-rw-r--r--.  1 root root    662 29 may   2021 logrotate.conf\n"
"-rw-r--r--.  1 root root    272 17 may.   2021 mailcap\n"
"-rw-------.  1 root root    122 12 may.  2021 securetty\n"
"...\n"
"-rw-r--r--.  2 root root     85 18 may.  17:04 resolv.conf\n"
"-rw-r--r--.  1 root root     44 18 may.  17:04 adjtime\n"
"-rw-r--r--.  1 root root    283 18 may.  17:05 mtab\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:542
msgid ""
"List `/var` files larger than 1 megabyte but less than 1 gigabyte. The "
"example here uses advanced `grep` commands with regular expressions. Novices "
"don't have to struggle too much, there will be a special tutorial to "
"introduce these regular expressions in the future."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:543
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ ls -lhR /var/ | grep ^\\- | grep -E \"[1-9]*\\.[0-9]*M\" \n"
"...\n"
"-rw-r--r--. 1 apache apache 1.2M 10 may.  13:02 XB RiyazBdIt.ttf\n"
"-rw-r--r--. 1 apache apache 1.2M 10 may.  13:02 XB RiyazBd.ttf\n"
"-rw-r--r--. 1 apache apache 1.1M 10 may.  13:02 XB RiyazIt.ttf\n"
"...\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:553
msgid "Of course, we highly recommend that you use the `find` command."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:554
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ find /var -size +1M -a -size -1024M  -a -type f  -exec ls -lh {} \\;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:559
msgid "Show the rights on a folder:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:561
msgid ""
"To find out the rights to a folder, in our example `/etc`, the following "
"command would **not** be appropriate:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:562
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ ls -l /etc\n"
"total 1332\n"
"-rw-r--r--.  1 root root     44 18 nov.  17:04 adjtime\n"
"-rw-r--r--.  1 root root   1512 12 janv.  2010 aliases\n"
"-rw-r--r--.  1 root root  12288 17 nov.  17:41 aliases.db\n"
"drwxr-xr-x.  2 root root   4096 17 nov.  17:48 alternatives\n"
"...\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:573
msgid ""
"The above command will display the contents of the folder (inside) by "
"default. For the folder itself, you can use the `-d` option."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:574
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ ls -ld /etc\n"
"drwxr-xr-x. 69 root root 4096 18 nov.  17:05 /etc\n"
