#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:632
#, no-wrap
msgid "`touch` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:635
msgid ""
"The `touch` command changes the timestamp of a file or creates an empty file "
"if the file does not exist."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:636
#, no-wrap
msgid "touch [-t date] file\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:642
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ touch /home/rockstar/myfile\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:649
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                            | Information                                                                |\n"
"| --------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-t date`                         | Changes the date of last modification of the file with the specified date. |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:651
msgid "Date format: `[AAAA]MMJJhhmm[ss]`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:655
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The `touch` command is primarily used to create an empty file, but it can be useful for incremental or differential backups for example. Indeed, the only effect of executing a `touch` on a file will be to force it to be saved during the next backup.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:656
#, no-wrap
msgid "`rmdir` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:659
msgid "The `rmdir` command deletes an empty directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:662
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ rmdir /home/rockstar/work\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:669
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                                                                  | Information |\n"
"| ----------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------- |\n"
"| `-p` |  Removes the parent directory or directories provided if they are empty.           |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:673
#, no-wrap
msgid "    To delete both a non-empty directory and its contents, use the `rm` command.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:674
#, no-wrap
msgid "`rm` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:677
msgid "The `rm` command deletes a file or directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:678
#, no-wrap
msgid "rm [-f] [-r] file [file] [...]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:685
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Any deletion of a file or directory is final.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:691
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Options | Information                              |\n"
"| ------- | ---------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-f`    | Do not ask whether to delete. |\n"
"| `-i`    | Ask whether to delete.       |\n"
"| `-r`    | Delete a directory and recursively delete its subdirectories.      |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:695
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The `rm` command itself does not ask for confirmation when deleting files. However, with a Red Hat/Rocky distribution, `rm` does ask for confirmation of deletion because the `rm` command is an `alias` of the `rm -i` command. Don't be surprised if on another distribution, like Debian for example, you don't get a confirmation request.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:697
msgid ""
"Deleting a folder with the `rm` command, whether the folder is empty or not, "
"will require the `-r` option to be added."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:699
msgid "The end of the options is signaled to the shell by a double dash `--`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:701
msgid "In the example:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:702
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ >-hard-hard # To create an empty file called -hard-hard\n"
"hard-hard\n"
"[CTRL+C] To interrupt the creation of the file\n"
"$ rm -f -- -hard-hard\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:710
msgid ""
"The hard-hard file name starts with a `-`. Without the use of the `--` the "
"shell would have interpreted the `-d` in `-hard-hard` as an option."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:711
#, no-wrap
msgid "`mv` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:714
msgid "The `mv` command moves and renames a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:715
#, no-wrap
msgid "mv file [file ...] destination\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:721
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ mv /home/rockstar/file1 /home/rockstar/file2\n"
"$ mv /home/rockstar/file1 /home/rockstar/file2 /tmp\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:730
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Options                                                                        | Information                                                     |\n"
"| ------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | --------------------------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-f`                                                                           | Don't ask for confirmation if overwriting the destination file. |\n"
"| `-i`                                                                           | Request confirmation if overwriting destination file (default). |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:732
msgid ""
"A few concrete cases will help you understand the difficulties that can "
"arise:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:733
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ mv /home/rockstar/file1 /home/rockstar/file2\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:738
msgid ""
"Renames `file1` to `file2`. If `file2` already exists, replace the contents "
"of the file with `file1`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:739
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ mv /home/rockstar/file1 /home/rockstar/file2 /tmp\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:744
msgid "Moves `file1` and `file2` into the `/tmp` directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:745
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ mv file1 /repexist/file2\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:750
msgid "Moves `file1` into `repexist` and renames it `file2`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:751
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ mv file1 file2\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:756
msgid "`file1` is renamed to `file2`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:757
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ mv file1 /repexist\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:762
msgid "If the destination directory exists, `file1` is moved to `/repexist`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:763
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ mv file1 /wrongrep\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:768
msgid ""
"If the destination directory does not exist, `file1` is renamed to "
"`wrongrep` in the root directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:769
#, no-wrap
msgid "`cp` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:772
msgid "The `cp` command copies a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:773
#, no-wrap
msgid "cp file [file ...] destination\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:779
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ cp -r /home/rockstar /tmp\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:790
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Options | Information                                                      |\n"
"| ------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-i`    | Request confirmation if overwriting (default).                   |\n"
"| `-f`    | Do not ask for confirmation if overwriting the destination file. |\n"
"| `-p`    | Keeps the owner, permissions and timestamp of the copied file.   |\n"
"| `-r`    | Copies a directory with its files and subdirectories.            |\n"
"| `-s`    | Creates a symbolic link rather than copying.                    |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:791
#, no-wrap
msgid "cp file1 /repexist/file2\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:796
msgid "`file1` is copied to `/repexist` under the name `file2`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:797
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ cp file1 file2\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:802
msgid "`file1` is copied as `file2` to this directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:803
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ cp file1 /repexist\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:808
msgid "If the destination directory exists, `file1` is copied to `/repexist`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:809
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ cp file1 /wrongrep\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:814
msgid ""
"If the destination directory does not exist, `file1` is copied under the "
"name `wrongrep` to the root directory."
msgstr ""

