#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:929
msgid "Example: Display a log file by displaying the last line first:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:930
#, no-wrap
msgid "[root]# tac /var/log/messages | less\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:934
#, no-wrap
msgid "`head` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:937
msgid "The `head` command displays the beginning of a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:938
#, no-wrap
msgid "head [-n x] file\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:945
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                                                                                                | Description                            |\n"
"| ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-n x`                                                                                                | Display the first `x` lines of the file |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:947
msgid ""
"By default (without the `-n` option), the `head` command will display the "
"first 10 lines of the file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:948
#, no-wrap
msgid "`tail` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:951
msgid "The `tail` command displays the end of a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:952
#, no-wrap
msgid "tail [-f] [-n x] file\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:960
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option   | Description                             |\n"
"| -------- | ----------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-n x`   | Displays the last `x` lines of the file   |\n"
"| `-f`     | Displays changes to the file in real time |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:963
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"tail -n 3 /etc/passwd\n"
"sshd:x:74:74:Privilege-separeted sshd:/var/empty /sshd:/sbin/nologin\n"
"tcpdump::x:72:72::/:/sbin/nologin\n"
"user1:x:500:500:grp1:/home/user1:/bin/bash\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:971
#, no-wrap
msgid "With the `-f` option, the change information of the file will always be output unless the user exits the monitoring state with <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>C</kbd>. This option is very frequently used to track log files (the logs) in real time.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:973
msgid ""
"Without the `-n` option, the `tail` command displays the last 10 lines of "
"the file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:974
#, no-wrap
msgid "`sort` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:977
msgid "The `sort` command sorts the lines of a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:979
msgid ""
"It allows you to order the result of a command or the content of a file in a "
"given order, numerically, alphabetically, by size (KB, MB, GB) or in reverse "
"order."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:980
#, no-wrap
msgid "sort [-k] [-n] [-u] [-o file] [-t] file\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:986
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ sort -k 3,4 -t \":\" -n /etc/passwd\n"
"root:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash\n"
"adm:x:3:4:adm:/var/adm/:/sbin/nologin\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1000
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option    | Description                              |\n"
"| --------- | ------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-k`     | Specify the columns to be separated. You can specify multiple columns.         |\n"
"| `-n`      | Requests a numeric sort.                     |\n"
"| `-o file` | Saves the sort to the specified file.        |\n"
"| `-t`     | Specify a delimiter, which requires that the contents of the corresponding file must be regularly delimited column contents, otherwise they cannot be sorted properly. |\n"
"| `-r`      | Reverse the order of the result. Used in conjunction with the `-n` option to sort in order from largest to smallest.             |\n"
"| `-u`     | Remove duplicates after sorting. Equivalent to `sort file | uniq`.                   |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1002
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `sort` command sorts the file only on the screen. The file is not modified by the sorting. To save the sort, use the `-o` option or an output redirection `>`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1004
msgid ""
"By default, the numbers are sorted according to their character. Thus, "
"\"110\" will be before \"20\", which will itself be before \"3\". The `-n` "
"option must be specified so that the numeric character blocks are sorted by "
"their value."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1006
msgid ""
"The `sort` command reverses the order of the results, with the `-r` option:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1007
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ sort -k 3 -t \":\" -n -r /etc/passwd\n"
"nobody:x:65534:65534:Kernel Overflow User:/:/sbin/nologin\n"
"systemd-coredump:x:999:997:systemd Core Dumper:/:/sbin/nologin\n"
"polkitd:x:998:996:User for polkitd:/:/sbin/nologin\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1015
msgid ""
"In this example, the `sort` command will sort the contents of the `/etc/"
"passwd` file this time from largest uid (user identifier) to smallest."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1017
msgid "Some advanced examples of using the `sort` command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1019
msgid "Shuffling values"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1021
msgid ""
"The `sort` command also allows you to shuffle values with the `-R` option:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1022
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ sort -R /etc/passwd\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1027
msgid "Sorting IP addresses"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1029
msgid ""
"A system administrator is quickly confronted with the processing of IP "
"addresses from the logs of his services such as SMTP, VSFTP or Apache. These "
"addresses are typically extracted with the `cut` command."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1031
msgid "Here is an example with the file `dns-client.txt`:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1032
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"192.168.1.10\n"
"192.168.1.200\n"
"5.1.150.146\n"
"208.128.150.98\n"
"208.128.150.99\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1040
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ sort -nr dns-client.txt\n"
"208.128.150.99\n"
"208.128.150.98\n"
"192.168.1.200\n"
"192.168.1.10\n"
"5.1.150.146\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1050
msgid "Sorting file by removing duplicates"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1052
msgid ""
"The `sort` command knows how to remove the duplicates from the file output "
"using `-u` as option."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1054
msgid "Here is an example with the file `colours.txt`:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1055
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Red\n"
"Green\n"
"Blue\n"
"Red\n"
"Pink\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1062
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ sort -u colours.txt\n"
"Blue\n"
"Green\n"
"Pink\n"
"Red\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1071
msgid "Sorting file by sizes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1073
msgid ""
"The `sort` command knows how to recognize file sizes, from commands like "
"`ls` with the `-h` option."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1075
msgid "Here is an example with the file `size.txt`:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1076
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"1.7G\n"
"18M\n"
"69K\n"
"2.4M\n"
"1.2M\n"
"4.2G\n"
"6M\n"
"124M\n"
"12.4M\n"
"4G\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1089
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ sort -hr size.txt\n"
"4.2G\n"
"4G\n"
"1.7G\n"
"124M\n"
"18M\n"
"12.4M\n"
"6M\n"
"2.4M\n"
"1.2M\n"
"69K\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1103
#, no-wrap
msgid "`wc` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1106
msgid ""
"The `wc` command counts the number of lines, words and/or bytes in a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1107
#, no-wrap
msgid "wc [-l] [-m] [-w] file [files]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1117
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option | Description                    |\n"
"| ------ | ------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-c`   | Count the number of bytes.      |\n"
"| `-m`   | Count the number of characters. |\n"
"| `-l`   | Counts the number of lines.     |\n"
"| `-w`   | Counts the number of words.     |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1118
#, no-wrap
msgid "Search"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1120
#, no-wrap
msgid "`find` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1123
msgid "The `find` command searches for files or directories location."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1124
#, no-wrap
msgid "find directory [-name name] [-type type] [-user login] [-date date]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1129
msgid ""
"Since there are so many options to the `find` command, it is best to refer "
"to the `man`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1131
msgid ""
"If the search directory is not specified, the `find` command will search "
"from the current directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1136
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option              | Description                            |\n"
"| ------------------- | -------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-perm permissions` | Search for files by their permissions. |\n"
"| `-size size`        | Search for files by size.              |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1137
#, no-wrap
msgid "`-exec` option of the `find` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1140
msgid ""
"It is possible to use the `-exec` option of the `find` command to execute a "
"command on each result line:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1141
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ find /tmp -name *.txt -exec rm -f {} \\;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1146
msgid ""
"The previous command searches for all files in the `/tmp` directory named `*."
"txt` and deletes them."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1148
msgid "!!! Tip \"Understand the `-exec` option\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1150
#, no-wrap
msgid "    In the example above, the `find` command will construct a string representing the command to be executed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1152
#, no-wrap
msgid "    If the `find` command finds three files named `log1.txt`, `log2.txt`, and `log3.txt`, then the `find` command will construct the string by replacing in the string `rm -f {} \\;` the braces with one of the results of the search, and do this as many times as there are results.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1154
#, no-wrap
msgid "    This will give us:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1158
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    ```\n"
"    rm -f /tmp/log1.txt ; rm -f /tmp/log2.txt ; rm -f /tmp/log3.txt ;\n"
"    ```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1160
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The `;` character is a special shell character that must be protected by a `\\` to prevent it from being interpreted too early by the `find` command (and not in the `-exec`).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1164
#, no-wrap
msgid "    `$ find /tmp -name *.txt -delete` does the same thing.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1165
#, no-wrap
msgid "`whereis` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1168
msgid "The `whereis` command searches for files related to a command."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1169
#, no-wrap
msgid "whereis [-b] [-m] [-s] command\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1175
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ whereis -b ls\n"
"ls: /bin/ls\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1185
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option | Description                     |\n"
"| ------ | ------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-b`   | Searches only the binary file.    |\n"
"| `-m`   | Searches only for man pages.    |\n"
"| `-s`   | Searches only for source files. |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1186
#, no-wrap
msgid "`grep` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1189
msgid "The `grep` command searches for a string in a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1190
#, no-wrap
msgid "grep [-w] [-i] [-v] \"string\" file\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1196
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ grep -w \"root:\" /etc/passwd\n"
"root:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1206
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                                                                                  | Description                             |\n"
"| --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-i`                                                                                    | Ignores the case of the searched string. |\n"
"| `-v`                                                                                    | Excludes lines containing the string.   |\n"
"| `-w`                                                                                    | Searches for the exact word.              |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1210
msgid ""
"The `grep` command returns the complete line containing the string you are "
"looking for.  * The `^` special character is used to search for a string at "
"the beginning of a line.  * The special character `$` searches for a string "
"at the end of a line."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1211
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ grep -w \"^root\" /etc/passwd\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1218
#, no-wrap
msgid "    This command is very powerful and it is highly recommended to consult its manual. It has many derivatives.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1220
msgid ""
"It is possible to search for a string in a file tree with the `-R` option."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1221
#, no-wrap
msgid "grep -R \"Virtual\" /etc/httpd\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1225
#, no-wrap
msgid "Meta-characters (wildcards)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1228
msgid ""
"Meta-characters replace one or more characters (or even an absence of "
"characters) during a search. These meta-characters are also known as "
"wildcards."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1230
msgid "They can be combined."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1232
msgid ""
"The `*` character replaces a string composed of any characters. The `*` "
"character can also represent an absence of character."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1233
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ find /home -name \"test*\"\n"
"/home/rockstar/test\n"
"/home/rockstar/test1\n"
"/home/rockstar/test11\n"
"/home/rockstar/tests\n"
"/home/rockstar/test362\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1243
msgid ""
"Meta-characters allow more complex searches by replacing all or part of a "
"word. Simply replace the unknowns with these special characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1245
msgid "The character `?` replaces a single character, whatever it is."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1246
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ find /home -name \"test?\"\n"
"/home/rockstar/test1\n"
"/home/rockstar/tests\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1253
msgid ""
"The square brackets `[` and `]` are used to specify the values that a single "
"character can take."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1254
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ find /home -name \"test[123]*\"\n"
"/home/rockstar/test1\n"
"/home/rockstar/test11\n"
"/home/rockstar/test362\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1264
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Always surround words containing meta-characters with `\"` to prevent them from being replaced by the names of files that meet the criteria.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1268
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Do not confuse shell meta-characters with regular expression meta-characters. The `grep` command uses regular expression meta-characters.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1269
#, no-wrap
msgid "Redirects and pipes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1271
#, no-wrap
msgid "Standard input and output"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1274
msgid ""
"On UNIX and Linux systems, there are three standard streams. They allow "
"programs, via the `stdio.h` library, to input or output information."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1276
msgid "These streams are called X channel or X file descriptor."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1278
msgid "By default:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1281
msgid "the keyboard is the input device for channel 0, called **stdin** ;"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1281
msgid ""
"the screen is the output device for channels 1 and 2, called **stdout** and "
"**stderr**."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1283
msgid "![standards channels](images/input-output.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1285
#, no-wrap
msgid "**stderr** receives the error streams returned by a command. The other streams are directed to **stdout**.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1287
msgid ""
"These streams point to peripheral files, but since everything is a file in "
"UNIX/Linux, I/O streams can easily be diverted to other files. This "
"principle is the strength of the shell."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1288
#, no-wrap
msgid "Input redirection"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1291
#, no-wrap
msgid "It is possible to redirect the input stream from another file with the character `<` or `<<`. The command will read the file instead of the keyboard:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1292
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ ftp -in serverftp << ftp-commands.txt\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1299
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Only commands that require keyboard input will be able to handle input redirection.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1301
msgid ""
"Input redirection can also be used to simulate user interactivity. The "
"command will read the input stream until it encounters the defined keyword "
"after the input redirection."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1303
msgid "This feature is used to script interactive commands:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1304
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ ftp -in serverftp << END\n"
"user alice password\n"
"put file\n"
"bye\n"
"END\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1313
msgid "The keyword `END` can be replaced by any word."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1314
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ ftp -in serverftp << STOP\n"
"user alice password\n"
"put file\n"
"bye\n"
"STOP\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1323
msgid ""
"The shell exits the `ftp` command when it receives a line containing only "
"the keyword."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1327
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The ending keyword, here `END` or `STOP`, must be the only word on the line and must be at the beginning of the line.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1329
msgid ""
"The standard input redirection is rarely used because most commands accept a "
"filename as an argument."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1331
msgid "The command `wc` could be used like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1332
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ wc -l .bash_profile\n"
"27 .bash_profile # the number of lines is followed by the file name\n"
"$ wc -l < .bash_profile\n"
"27 # returns only the number of lines\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1339
#, no-wrap
msgid "Output redirection"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1342
#, no-wrap
msgid "Standard output can be redirected to other files using the `>` or `>>` characters.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1344
#, no-wrap
msgid "The simple `>` redirection overwrites the contents of the output file:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1345
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ date +%F > date_file\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1350
#, no-wrap
msgid "When the `>>` character is used, it indicates that the output result of the command is appended to the file content.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1351
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ date +%F >> date_file\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1356
msgid ""
"In both cases, the file is automatically created when it does not exist."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1358
msgid ""
"The standard error output can also be redirected to another file. This time "
"it will be necessary to specify the channel number (which can be omitted for "
"channels 0 and 1):"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1359
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ ls -R / 2> errors_file\n"
"$ ls -R / 2>> errors_file\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1364
#, no-wrap
msgid "Examples of redirection"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1367
msgid "Redirection of 2 outputs to 2 files:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1368
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ ls -R / >> ok_file 2>> nok_file\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1373
msgid "Redirection of the 2 outputs to a single file:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1374
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ ls -R / >> log_file 2>&1\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1379
msgid "Redirection of *stderr* to a \"bottomless pit\" (`/dev/null`):"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1380
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ ls -R / 2>> /dev/null\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1385
msgid ""
"When both output streams are redirected, no information is displayed on the "
"screen. To use both the output redirection and to keep the display, you will "
"have to use the command `tee`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1386
#, no-wrap
msgid "Pipes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1389
msgid ""
"A **pipe** is a mechanism allowing you to link the standard output of a "
"first command to the standard input of a second command."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1391
#, no-wrap
msgid "This communication is uni directional and is done with the `|` symbol. The pipe symbol `|` is obtained by pressing the  <kbd>SHIFT</kbd> + <kbd>|</kbd> simultaneously.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1393
msgid "![pipe](images/pipe.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1395
msgid ""
